          <header>
            <h2>
              <a href="/2016/2/27/Rails-5-0-beta3/" rel="bookmark">Rails 5.0.0.beta3: More fixes, RC1 is soon</a>
            </h2>
            <p class="entry-meta">
              Posted by <span class="vcard"><span class="fn">dhh</span></span>,
              <span class="published" title="2016-02-27 16:00:00 +0000">February 27, 2016 @  4:00 pm</span>
              
                <span class="categories">in
              
              
                  <a href="/releases/" rel="category tag">Releases</a>
              
              
                </span>
              
            </p>
          </header>
          <section>
<!-- Begin Post -->
<p>We‚Äôre currently down to <a href="https://github.com/rails/rails/milestones/5.0.0">18 open issues</a> on the issue tracker for Rails 5.0.0.RC1. But while we continue to drive that number down, we thought it‚Äôd be nice to release another beta with the many fixes and updates we‚Äôve seen since beta2. We‚Äôve had some <a href="https://github.com/rails/rails/compare/v5.0.0.beta2...v5.0.0.beta3">500+ commits pass since that release</a>, and for people testing out Rails 5.0, it‚Äôs just a better release.</p>

<p>The release targets have been moved out a bit, so RC1 on March 1 and then final on March 16. That may well be a tad optimistic still, but that‚Äôs the current target.</p>

<p>If you missed the announcement on what‚Äôs new in Rails 5, <a href="http://weblog.rubyonrails.org/2015/12/18/Rails-5-0-beta1/">checkout the beta1 story</a>. Thanks to Eileen Uchitelle for coordinating this release.</p>

<!-- End Post -->
          </section>
        </article>


        <article>
          <header>
            <h2>
              <a href="/2016/2/2/Rails-5-0-beta2/" rel="bookmark">Rails 5.0.0.beta2: Slashed Action Cable dependencies, fixes galore</a>
            </h2>
            <p class="entry-meta">
              Posted by <span class="vcard"><span class="fn">dhh</span></span>,
              <span class="published" title="2016-02-02 16:00:00 +0000">February 2, 2016 @  4:00 pm</span>
              
                <span class="categories">in
              
              
                  <a href="/releases/" rel="category tag">Releases</a>
              
              
                </span>
              
            </p>
          </header>
          <section>
<!-- Begin Post -->
<p>Progress waits for nobody: The second beta release of Rails 5 is out, and it‚Äôs packed with a six weeks worth of fixes and upgrades.</p>

<p>The big news is that Action Cable no longer depends on Celluloid, Redis, or even EventMachine! We‚Äôve doubled down on concurrent-ruby, added a PostgreSQL alternative adapter to Redis for pubsub, and added a non-EventMachine Redis adapter too. So if you were freaking out over the new dependencies in beta1, you can breathe easy again. The Rails community has, as per-usual, stepped up and Made It Better. Special thanks to Mike Perham, Jon Moss, and Matthew Draper for their work on this!</p>

<p>Beyond that, there‚Äôs literally <a href="https://github.com/rails/rails/commits/v5.0.0.beta2?page=25">25 pages of commits on GitHub</a> detailing the work done since the beta1 release on December 18. It‚Äôs a good stroll through the work it takes to go from beta to beta.</p>

<p>The release targets from here are RC1 on February 16 and then final on February 23. All depends on how much stuff pops up from beta2 and RC1, though. So don‚Äôt order cake or champagne for delivery on those dates just yet!</p>

<p>If you missed the announcement on what‚Äôs new in Rails 5, <a href="http://weblog.rubyonrails.org/2015/12/18/Rails-5-0-beta1/">checkout the beta1 story</a>. Oh, and thanks to Sean Griffin for coordinating this release.</p>

<!-- End Post -->
          </section>
        </article>


