        <article>
          <header>
            <h2>
              <a href="/2014/2/18/Rails-4-1-rc1/" rel="bookmark">Rails 4.1.0: Release candidate 1</a>
            </h2>
            <p class="entry-meta">
              Posted by <span class="vcard"><span class="fn">dhh</span></span>,
              <span class="published" title="2014-02-18 20:30:00 +0000">February 18, 2014 @  8:30 pm</span>
              
                <span class="categories">in
              
              
                  <a href="/releases/" rel="category tag">Releases</a>
              
              
                </span>
              
            </p>
          </header>
          <section>
<!-- Begin Post -->
<p>We‚Äôre getting really close to signing off on Rails 4.1.0, but we need your help to push it the last mile. Today we‚Äôre putting out the first (and, with luck, only) release candidate of Rails 4.1.0. It would be swell if you would try it out and tell us where it breaks.</p>

<p>It‚Äôs already in really good shape (we‚Äôve been running beta1 and forward in production for <a href="http://basecamp.com">Basecamp</a> for months), but still, let‚Äôs make it a shiny gemstone for release.</p>

<p>As a reminder, Yves and Godfrey have done such a splendid job putting together the <a href="http://edgeguides.rubyonrails.org/4_1_release_notes.html">release notes for 4.1 as a guide</a> and <a href="http://coherence.io/blog/2013/12/17/whats-new-in-rails-4-1.html">Godfrey‚Äôs feature walk-through</a>, so I won‚Äôt repeat them here. But you‚Äôre definitely in for a treat.</p>

<p>We have also now aimed rails/master at Rails 4.2.0, but there‚Äôs a new <a href="https://github.com/rails/rails/tree/4-1-stable">rails/4-1-stable</a> branch to follow for this release series. And of course there‚Äôs the <a href="https://github.com/rails/rails/tree/v4.1.0.rc1">v4-1-0-rc1 tag</a> for this particular release.</p>

<p>Enjoy!</p>

<!-- End Post -->
          </section>
        </article>


        <article>
          <header>
